      "text": "  Then the union of  $S(d,t)$  for all such  $d$  and  $t$  is a subset of  $I \\times I$ . This union indeed contains all elements of  $I \\times I$ . To see this, let  $(x,y) \\in I \\times I$  and let  $d = (ax+by,n)$ . Pick  $1 \\le t \\le \\frac{n}{d}$  such that  $t \\equiv \\frac{ax+by}{d} \\pmod{\\frac{n}{d}}$ . Then  $(t, \\frac{n}{d}) = 1$  and  $ax + by \\equiv td \\pmod{n}$ . Thus,  $(x,y) \\in S(d,t)$ . Finally, if  $S(d,t) \\cap S(d',t') \\neq \\emptyset$ , then choose one pair  $(x,y)$  in this intersection. We obtain  $d = (ax+by,n) = d'$ . Furthermore,  $td \\equiv t'd \\pmod{n}$  implies that  $t \\equiv t' \\pmod{\\frac{n}{d}}$ . Since  $1 \\le t, t' \\le \\frac{n}{d}$ , we have  $t = t'$ .  $\\Box$ ",
